#welcome!
this tutorial explains how to implement and use images ![no image]() 
click on the **play button** ![play button](playbutton.svg) to begin the presentation.

and remember: we don't save changes in the tutorials, so you can hit `escape` and freely play around in this slidenote any time.

---
## images in slidenotes: a piece of cake

+++layout:left
![cake](piece-of-cake.jpg)
+++

+++layout:right
images are a useful and sometimes even necessary way to enhance your presentation.

that's why you can also implement pictures in your slidenotes.

while our presentations are not meant to be heavily image based *(because let's face it: there are better solutions for design centered approaches)* it's very easy to apply pictures to your slides whenever you need them.

*just go to the ![toolbar button](toolbar.svg) **toolbar**, press the `![](image)` button and the upload dialog will open. that's it!*

but if you want to learn more about what you can do with images—we got you ➡︎
+++

---
##the image tag

+++layout:left
in slidenotes, images are represented with a markdown image tag: 
 
+++code
![image description](image name)
+++
all text inside the square brackets ~[]~ will be interpreted as the ~[image description]~. though the image description is invisible in the presentation, it will be displayed if the image doesn't load and is read by screen readers.
we highly recommend using the description as it makes your content more accessible.
however, if you know your audience and are sure that nobody depends on it, you can leave this part blank:

+++code
![](image name)
+++

the text in the brackets ~()~ displays the ~(name of your image)~. 
this doesn't necessarily have to be the file name of your image: we implemented an easy click and point solution which works without you doing any coding and lets you choose your image names yourself.
+++

---
## default image

+++layout:left
image names work like unique identification codes that connect image tags to certain images. 
so whenever you are using an image tag with an image name that does not connect to any name of the pictures in your image gallery, slidenotes will alert you by marking the code in red:
 ![](marking-missing-image) 
as long as you don't fix it, slidenotes will fill in its default image as a place holder.
the same happens if don't put in any name at all.
+++

+++layout:right
![](this image name does not exist in the gallery)
+++

---
## uploading image files

+++layout:left
before you can implement any image tag in the code of your slidenotes, you need to attach the actual image file to your slidenote document:

1. click on the **image gallery button** ![image gallery button](image-gallery.svg) at the top right of your screen
2. click on **+ add image**
3. select an image from your local files
4. choose the size and quality of the image as needed

now your image file is stored (and encrypted!) inside your slidenote document.
by opening the **image gallery** ![image gallery button](image-gallery.svg) you can look it up at any time and check where it is used.

now let's display it on a slide ➡︎
+++

----
## attaching images to slides

one way to attach a picture to a slide is this:

1. in your text, click on the text passage where the image should go
2. click on the **image gallery button** ![image gallery button](image-gallery.svg) at the top right of your screen
3. choose one of your uploaded images

now, the image tag has been applied to your code. 

your only remaining task—if needed—is to add an ~[image description]~ inside the square brackets ~[]~.

---
## speed up the process
*(optional)*

+++layout:left
once you're used to image tags, you can employ them to speed up your workflow:

everytime you're working on a slide and get to a point where a new image should be, you can upload, name and attach it—all at the same time.
all you need to do is this:

type in an image tag with an image name of your choice:

+++code 
![](look at me i totally made that name just up)
+++

when you're done, a pop up window will open the **image gallery**.
click on **+ add image** and select an image from your local file system.

and boom. this image is now:
- uploaded and stored in your **image gallery**
- using the name you just made up
- and as such attached to the slide you're working on

crazy fast, right?
+++

---
## naming images

naming your pictures yourself instead of using given file names has a lot of advantages.

first of all it helps you to coordinate your images and tags in a way that makes sense to you.

second of all it is key to unleash another useful feature here at slidenotes.io which is: replacing images.

let's learn how to use that ➡︎

----
## how to replace images 

+++layout:left
let's say you uploaded an image of a cat. 
![cat](cat 1)
and you used this image over and over 'cause—what's a slide without a cat?

so your code might look something like that:

+++code:none
---
my studies have shown that I like cats. ![cat](cat)
---- start slide 2
my future outlook is that I'll like cats. ![cat](cat)
---- start slide 3
do you have any questions about cats? ![cat](cat)
+++

you have already used your cat image on 23 different slides when suddenly you come across the picture of a moving cat. even better!
![](cat 2)
so what now? let's sort this out ➡︎
+++

---
## how to replace images: one

if you decide to replace only one of the pictures, you can do this by changing the image name in this one specific image tag.

1. upload your replacement image to the **image gallery** as learned
2. click inside the image name in the image tag of the picture you want to replace (for example the one on slide 2)
3. click on the **image gallery button** ![](image-gallery.svg) at the top right of your screen
4. select the replacement image

now the image name of this image tag has been changed to the name of your new picture:

+++code
my studies have shown that I like cats. ![](cat)
---- start slide 2
my future outlook is that I'll like cats. ![](even_cuter_cat.png)
---- start slide 3
do you have any questions about cats? ![](cat)
+++

----
## how to replace images: various

now, if you decide to replace all of the pictures, the possibility to name and rename images comes in really handy: because this way, you don't have to replace every image name in every image tag on every slide. instead, you can just connect the new image to the old image tags by doing the following:

1. click into any of the image tags you want to replace
2. click on the **image context menu** ![](context-menu_image) that shows up at the beginning of the line
3. click on **image search** ![](context-menu_image-search.svg)
4. click on **+ add image**
5. select the replacement image from your local file system

and that's it: now your new picture uploaded and was given the image name of your former image. 
this way it ends up on every single slide you used the old one on ![](cat 2) ![](cat 2) ![](cat 2). 
meanwhile the old one stays in your image gallery as *(unnamed)*.

---
## background images: for whole slides

+++layout:left
images will be displayed as the background of a slide, whenever they are declared in the very first line of a slide, followed by an empty line:
+++

+++layout:right
+++code
![](background images name)

my first slide with a background image.
---- start slide 2
![](different images name)

this slide has a different background image.
+++
if you don't want to code this by hand, you can get there by doing the following ➡︎
+++

----
## background images: for whole slides

while working on your slide:

1. click on the **image gallery** ![](image-gallery.svg)
2. click on the image you want to use as the background for your slide
3. click inside the image tag that appeared on your slide
4. click on the **image context menu** ![](context-menu_image) that shows up at the beginning of the line
5. select **set as background**

the image tag will now be put in the first line of your slide for you.

-----
## background images: for layout blocks

+++layout:left
just like an image tag put in the very first line of a slide makes it the slides' background picture, the same works for layout blocks too: 
whenever you put an image tag in the first line of a layout block, it fills up the whole background of the block. 
note that there has to be an empty line between the image tag and your text so that your text is displayed *on* the image and not beneath:
+++

+++layout:right
+++code:none
---
## headline of this slide

 +++layout:left
 ![](background image for left layout block)

 text inside left layout block
 +++

text on the rest of the slide
+++
+++

---

+++layout:left
do you want to try it yourself?
then change the background image of this slide. 
+++

+++layout:right
![](garlic-heaven.jpg)

and the background image of this layout block.
+++

## positioning images

as you now know, the place of the image tag in the code of a slide directly correlates with the position the image will be taking in the finished presentation.

so here's an overview over image tag positions and what they mean:

+++table
position of image tag in code; position of image on slide
inside the line of a title; inside the title and within its height
inside a line of text; as icons inside the text
alone in one line; bigger than an icon in the text
alone in the very first line of a slide / layout block, followed by an empty line; background of the slide / layout block
as the only content of a slide, but not in the first line; as big as possible, centered on the slide
+++

*note: if you want to keep control over these things, you should stay with the themes **minimalist** or **dark**, the other themes may use the rules more freely for more dearing designs*
 
---
## image subtitles

+++layout:left
![image of a dog](strawberries.jpg)
strawberries. obviously.
+++

sometimes, images require subtitles. 
you can set them whenever an image tag is the sole element of a line by filling in text in the line right beneath. 
this text will be interpreted as the image's subtitle—which means it will be displayed in a small font size and directly underneath.
if you want to go on with other text, just leave a line empty before typing. this way the editor knows that the following text doesn't belong to the image anymore.

+++code
![](image name)
text for the subtitle to the image

other text not belonging to the subtitle of the image
+++
 
---
## quality of images

as you know, every image you use in your slidenote will be directly attached to it.
in conclusion, the file size of your slidenote reflects the file sizes of its images.
more even as the encryption process increases the size.
therefore it's good practice to think about the image quality whenever you are attaching a file. 
you already noticed that we built in a feature in order to make this more easy for you: 
whenever you upload an image to the gallery, you can choose between the options **small**, **medium**, **large** and **original**.
keep in mind that resizing it will affect the images quality. so if you upload a picture as **small** you can only use it as an icon and not as a background image later on. 
also, the resizing process changes the file to a *.png* picture. so in case you want to upload a *.gif* animation make sure to use the option **original**.
